\begin_layout Standard
La derivada direccional de 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 en dirección 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 se escribe:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{u}f\left(x,y\right)=\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\frac{f\left(x_{0}+tcos\theta,y_{0}+sen\theta\right)-f\left(x_{0},y_{0}\right)}{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Si 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 es una función diferenciable en 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 e 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, entonces la derivada direccional de 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 en la dirección del vector unitario 
\begin_inset Formula $u=cos\theta i+sen\theta j$
\end_inset

 es
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{u}f\left(x,y\right)=f_{x}\left(x,y\right)cos\theta+f_{y}\left(x,y\right)sen\theta
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

